Hello there. My name is Dr. Sbaitso, and I created this project to introduce you  to segments in Descript.  To begin, press the play button in the bottom left.

Now look to the right of your screen. That's the map view. It's where you determine where you want your Detour-taker to hear the audio. If they were to walk this Detour right now, they'd hear all the content up to this point, as well as the next paragraph at 301 Grove. 

Don't believe me?  Look at the map and find the grey dot with the white cursor icon. It may be hiding underneath a red pin. If you're having trouble finding it, click the red 'IMG' pill to see what that icon looks like when it's not hiding. This is where the user is standing when they're hearing the words that you're reading right now. The script view and the map view are synched. So if you move your cursor to sections later in the Detour, that icon jumps to the place where the user will hear those sections. Go ahead and try it. Scroll down about 10 lines from here and watch that blue cursor icon.

Scroll down this line
And this one too
Even further please
Keep going 
A bit more
Are you seeing the cursor move yet?
Inch its way along the path?
Slowly but surely?
You'll see that icon move throughout this tutorial. It's a great timing tool. It lets you as a Detour creator approximate where the Detour taker is standing at each point of the Detour.

Alright, stop here for a moment. You now know the basic building blocks of a Detour - stop segments and walking segments. Those are at the root of every Detour we've made. 

Remember that the user doesn't know anything about these segments. They just hear a continuous story. It's your job as Detour-creator to use these segments wisely. You'll make choices about where to place triggers that start a new segment, and you'll use Descript's timing tools to help you out. 

 We've reached the end. I hope you are impressed by me, but really I just hope you understand me. I hope you were not overwhelmed by me.

Descript is still very early in its development cycle.  It will crash sometimes. It will change a lot, quickly. But it will always try its best. I will always try my best. And I hope you'll show me grace and in return I will always be open to your constructive criticism. Good bye.

The Flatiron Building, originally the Fuller Building, is a triangular 22-story steel-framed landmarked building located at 175 Fifth Avenue in the borough of Manhattan, New York City, and is considered to be a groundbreaking skyscraper.

Metronome is a large public art installation located along the south end of Union Square in New York City. The work was commissioned by the Related Companies, developers of One Union Square South, with the participation of the Public Art Fund and the Municipal Art Society. The $4.2 million provided by the developer makes it one of the largest private commissions of public art.
The artwork was created by Kristin Jones and Andrew Ginzel and consists of several sections, including a round circular void from which puffs of white steam are released throughout the day, and a clock made of large orange LED digits. Installation of Metronome began in February 1999, and its dedication took place on October 26, 1999.
